{"title_page": "The Coveted Mirror", "text_new": "{{Infobox video game\n| title = The Coveted Mirror\n| image = The Coveted Mirror Cover Art Apple II.jpg\n| alt = Coveted Mirror\n| caption = Apple II cover art\n| developer = Eagle Berns<br>Holly Thomason\n| publisher = [[Penguin Software]]\n| released = 1983\n| genre = [[Adventure game|Adventure]]\n| modes = [[Single player]]\n| platforms = [[Apple II]]\n}}\n\n'''''The Coveted Mirror''''' was a [[Graphic adventure game|graphical text-based adventure game]] published for the [[Apple ii|Apple II]]. It was created by Eagle Berns and Holly Thomason and released by [[Penguin Software]] in 1983.<ref>Title Screen, ''The Coveted Mirror''</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nThe land of Starbury was taken over by Voar the evil.  During his grasp for power, Voar tried to seize the magic mirror but broke it into five pieces; luckily, he was only able to grab four of the pieces. it is up to you, the hero, to find the fifth and final piece in order to break Voar's rule and save the people of Starbury.<ref>http://www.lysator.liu.se/adventure/Penguin_Software_Inc.html</ref>\n\n==Gameplay==\n[[File:Coveted mirror.jpg|left|thumb|163x163px|Screenshot of gameplay]]\n''The Coveted Mirror'' utilizes a [[text parser]], in which the player types commands to perform actions in the game.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://graphicsmagician.com/polarware/adventures.htm\n |title=Adventure Games\n |website=Polarware Archive site\n |publisher=Polarware\n |access-date=July 27, 2017}}</ref>\nAdditionally, part of the challenge of ''The Coveted Mirror'' involves frequent, timed escapes from the jail tower.  Within a limited timeframe, indicated by an hourglass, the player must search the castle, find objects, and talk to people and return to the cell by the time the jailer makes his rounds.  This timed element adds another dimension to the exploration and puzzle solving.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://archive.org/stream/PopularMechanics1984/Popular_Mechanics_04_1984#page/n51/mode/2up\n |title=The Evil King\n |last=Shapiro\n |first=Neil\n |date=April 1984\n |publisher=Popular Mechanics magazine\n |page=52\n |access-date=July 27, 2017\n}}</ref> The original version also included several little arcade style scenes that work into the solution of the adventure, such as a jousting game and a fishing game. The later ''Comprehend'' version<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://www.filfre.net/2014/06/comprehend/\n |title=Comprehend\n |last=Maher\n |first=Jimmy\n |publisher=The Digital Antiquarian\n |access-date=July 27, 2017\n}}</ref> released in 1986 replaced the two-word parser with a full-sentence parser and was released for more computer systems than the original Apple II version, but omitted the arcade-style scenes and replaced them with other puzzles.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://graphicsmagician.com/polarware/comprehend.htm\n |title=The Comprehend Adventures\n |website=Polarware Archive site\n |publisher=Polarware\n |access-date=July 27, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n''[[Softline (magazine)|Softline]]'' called ''The Coveted Mirror'' \"a great balance of magic and mystery\". The magazine liked the \"intelligent\" parser with built-in hints and the \"remarkably well done yet nonviolent\" arcade sequences, and concluded that it \"is probably the best graphic adventure of the year\".<ref name=\"pape19840102\">{{cite web\n |url=https://archive.org/stream/Softline_1984_01_02#page/n53/mode/2up\n |title=The Coveted Mirror\n |last=Pape\n |first=Jerry Jr.\n |date=Jan\u2013Feb 1984\n |publisher=Softline magazine\n |page=53\n |access-date=July 27, 2017\n}}\n</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of graphic adventure games]]\n*[[Penguin Software]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.virtualapple.org/covetedmirrordisk.html Play online] at [http://www.virtualapple.org/ Virtual Apple]\n*[http://www.answers.com/topic/the-coveted-mirror Game information]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Coveted Mirror, The}}\n[[Category:1983 video games]]\n[[Category:Adventure games]]\n[[Category:Apple II games]]\n[[Category:Apple II-only games]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox video game\n| title = The Coveted Mirror\n| image = The Coveted Mirror Cover Art Apple II.jpg\n| alt = Coveted Mirror\n| caption = Apple II cover art\n| developer = Eagle Berns<br>Holly Thomason\n| publisher = [[Penguin Software]]\n| released = 1983\n| genre = [[Adventure game|Adventure]]\n| modes = [[Single player]]\n| platforms = [[Apple II]]\n}}\n\n'''''The Coveted Mirror''''' was a [[Graphic adventure game|graphical text-based adventure game]] published for the [[Apple ii|Apple II]]. It was created by Eagle Berns and Holly Thomason and released by [[Penguin Software]] in 1983.<ref>Title Screen, ''The Coveted Mirror''</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nThe land of Starbury was taken over by Voar the evil.  During his grasp for power, Voar tried to seize the magic mirror but broke it into five pieces; luckily, he was only able to grab four of the pieces. it is up to you, the hero, to find the fifth and final piece in order to break Voar's rule and save the people of Starbury.<ref>http://www.lysator.liu.se/adventure/Penguin_Software_Inc.html</ref>\n\n==Gameplay==\n[[File:Coveted mirror.jpg|left|thumb|163x163px|Screenshot of gameplay]]\n''The Coveted Mirror'' utilizes a [[text parser]], in which the player types commands to perform actions in the game.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://graphicsmagician.com/polarware/adventures.htm\n |title=Adventure Games\n |website=Polarware Archive site\n |publisher=Polarware\n |access-date=July 27, 2017}}</ref>\nAdditionally, part of the challenge of ''The Coveted Mirror'' involves frequent, timed escapes from the jail tower.  Within a limited timeframe, indicated by an hourglass, the player must search the castle, find objects, and talk to people and return to the cell by the time the jailer makes his rounds.  This timed element adds another dimension to the exploration and puzzle solving.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://archive.org/stream/PopularMechanics1984/Popular_Mechanics_04_1984#page/n51/mode/2up\n |title=The Evil King\n |last=Shapiro\n |first=Neil\n |date=April 1984\n |publisher=Popular Mechanics magazine\n |page=52\n |access-date=July 27, 2017\n}}</ref> The original version also included several little arcade style scenes that work into the solution of the adventure, such as a jousting game and a fishing game. The later ''Comprehend'' version<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://www.filfre.net/2014/06/comprehend/\n |title=Comprehend\n |last=Maher\n |first=Jimmy\n |publisher=The Digital Antiquarian\n |access-date=July 27, 2017\n}}</ref> released in 1986 replaced the two-word parser with a full-sentence parser and was released for more computer systems than the original Apple II version, but omitted the arcade-style scenes and replaced them with other puzzles.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://graphicsmagician.com/polarware/comprehend.htm\n |title=The Comprehend Adventures\n |website=Polarware Archive site\n |publisher=Polarware\n |access-date=July 27, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n''[[Softline (magazine)|Softline]]'' called ''The Coveted Mirror'' \"a great balance of magic and mystery\". The magazine liked the \"intelligent\" parser with built-in hints and the \"remarkably well done yet nonviolent\" arcade sequences, and concluded that it \"is probably the best graphic adventure of the year\".<ref name=\"pape19840102\">{{cite web\n |url=https://archive.org/stream/Softline_1984_01_02#page/n53/mode/2up\n |title=The Coveted Mirror\n |last=Pape\n |first=Jerry Jr.\n |date=Jan\u2013Feb 1984\n |publisher=Softline magazine\n |page=53\n |access-date=July 27, 2017\n}}\n</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of graphic adventure games]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.virtualapple.org/covetedmirrordisk.html Play online] at [http://www.virtualapple.org/ Virtual Apple]\n*[http://www.answers.com/topic/the-coveted-mirror Game information]\n\n{